9","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1303":"1303","1237":"1237","1246":"1246","1224":"1224","1235":"1235","1212":"1212","1233":"1233","1211":"1211","1210":"1210","1208":"1208","Lowton, Lancashire, England":"Lowton, Lancashire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Winwick, Lancashire, England":"Winwick, Lancashire, England","Kenyon, Lancashire, England":"Kenyon, Lancashire, England"},"en":{"1208–1297":"1208–1297","1210–Female":"1210–Deceased","1211–Female":"1211–Deceased","1212–1297":"1212–1297","1230–1297":"1230–1297","1237–Male":"1237–Deceased","1231–Male":"1231–Deceased","1233–1303":"1233–1303","1235–Male":"1235–Deceased","1239–Female":"1239–Deceased","1183–Male":"1183–Deceased","1210–1246":"1210–1246","1297":"1297","1231":"1231","1230":"1230","1183":"1183","1239":"1239","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1303":"1303","1237":"1237","1246":"1246","1224":"1224","1235":"1235","1212":"1212","1233":"1233","1211":"1211","1210":"1210","1208":"1208","Lowton, Lancashire, England":"Lowton, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Winwick, Lancashire, England":"Winwick, Lancashire, England","Kenyon, Lancashire, England":"Kenyon, Lancashire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"De","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Kenyon","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Lancashire): habitational name from a place near Warrington, which is of uncertain etymology. There was formerly an ancient burial mound there and Ekwall has speculated that the name is a shortened form of a British name composed of the elements <i>crūc</i> ‘mound’ + a personal name cognate with Welsh <i>Einion</i> (see   Eynon  ).","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Coinín</b> ‘son of <i>Coinín</i>’, a byname based on a diminutive of <i>cano</i> ‘wolf’, also Anglicized as   Canning   and   Cunneen  . The similarity to the borrowed word <i>coinín</i> ‘coney, rabbit’ has sometimes caused this name to be Anglicized as   Rabbitt  .","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Fhinghin</b>, ‘son of Finghen’, a personal name meaning ‘fair-born’."],"variants":[{"name":"Kenion","meanings":["English (Lancashire): variant of   Kenyon  ."]},{"name":"Eynon","meanings":["Welsh: from <i>Enniaun</i>, an old Welsh personal name ultimately derived from Late Latin <i>Annianus</i>, but also associated with Welsh <i>einion</i> ‘anvil’, taken as implying stability and fortitude. See also   Beynon   and compare   Onion  ."]},{"name":"Kinion","meanings":["English and Irish: variant of   Kenyon  . Compare   Kinyon  ."]},{"name":"Kinyon","meanings":["English and Irish: variant of   Kenyon  . Compare   Kinion  ."]}]},{"name":"Jordon","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a name given to a child of either sex baptized in holy water that was, purportedly at least, brought from the River Jordan, whose Hebrew name, <i>ha-yarden</i>, means ‘flowing down’. It was in this river that Christ was baptized by John the Baptist, and medieval pilgrims to the Holy Land usually tried to bring back a flask of its water with them. The modern given name is either a revival of this, or else a transferred use of the surname that was derived from the medieval given name. It is more popular as a boy's name in Britain and as a girl's name in the United States."],"variants":[{"name":"Jordin","meanings":["Originally a name given to a child of either sex baptized in holy water that was, purportedly at least, brought from the River Jordan, whose Hebrew name, <i>ha-yarden</i>, means ‘flowing down’. It was in this river that Christ was baptized by John the Baptist, and medieval pilgrims to the Holy Land usually tried to bring back a flask of its water with them. The modern given name is either a revival of this, or else a transferred use of the surname that was derived from the medieval given name. It is more popular as a boy's name in Britain and as a girl's name in the United States."]},{"name":"Jordyn","meanings":["Originally a name given to a child of either sex baptized in holy water that was, purportedly at least, brought from the River Jordan, whose Hebrew name, <i>ha-yarden</i>, means ‘flowing down’. It was in this river that Christ was baptized by John the Baptist, and medieval pilgrims to the Holy Land usually tried to bring back a flask of its water with them. The modern given name is either a revival of this, or else a transferred use of the surname that was derived from the medieval given name. It is more popular as a boy's name in Britain and as a girl's name in the United States."]},{"name":"Jorden","meanings":["Originally a name given to a child of either sex baptized in holy water that was, purportedly at least, brought from the River Jordan, whose Hebrew name, <i>ha-yarden</i>, means ‘flowing down’. It was in this river that Christ was baptized by John the Baptist, and medieval pilgrims to the Holy Land usually tried to bring back a flask of its water with them. The modern given name is either a revival of this, or else a transferred use of the surname that was derived from the medieval given name. It is more popular as a boy's name in Britain and as a girl's name in the United States."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":7,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta